For this tutorial, we are also working with the mtcars dataset.

head(mtcars)

Basic requirements

  • Data must be a data frame/tibble (already pre-processed, ggplot2 only for visualization)
  • All plots require data (where does the data come from) and aesthetic mappings (which variable goes to which coordinates/"dimensions")
  • Mapping with aes()
In [ ]:
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp))

Background themes

Themes are one of the components/layers that control non-data ink.

First thing first: get rid of the (ugly) original theme/background. I like theme_bw a lot.

Many themes can be found here: https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/ggtheme.html or using the package ggthemes

In [ ]:
# Set theme for all following plots

theme_set(theme_bw())

Geometrics¶

First plot

Calling data and aesthetics creates no plot. Now comes the next question: Which types of plot do you make out of these variables?. This helps you to choose your geom layer.

With two continuous variables, you can make a scatterplot.

In [ ]:
ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + geom_point()

What are geoms?

You just picked your first geom. Simply put: Geoms (short for geometrics) represent the type of plot that you create. Essentially, this makes the plot visible to you.

geom_point is used to make scatterplots.

Can also use geom_line or geom_col -> Back to the question: Does it make sense?

In [ ]:
ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + geom_col()
ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + geom_line()

Geom needs correct input

Each geom has a different set of data input requirements.

The following histogram & bar plot both only require one input. What's the difference between these two plots?

In [ ]:
# Histogram allows only one variable input

ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) + geom_histogram()
In [ ]:
# Same thing with bar plot

ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = gear)) + geom_bar()

Aesthetic specifications

Various optional arguments allow for clearer formatting and presentation of the plots.

Each geom only understands a subset of these arguments.

  • color: border color, take names or hex code
  • shape: for scatterplot
  • fill: fill color, take names or hex code
  • alpha: transparency (0-1)
  • size
  • linetype: for line plot
  • lty: for line plot

More on this: https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/articles/ggplot2-specs.html

In [ ]:
# A line plot
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + geom_line(lty = "longdash", color = "red", size = 2, alpha = 0.3)
In [ ]:
# Bar plot from earlier
ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = gear)) + geom_bar(fill = "#15404e", color = "lightblue", size = 2)

Layering multiple geoms

Sometimes it is necessary to lay multiple geoms on top of each other.

geom_vline, geom_hline, geom_abline: for plotting a (vertical, horizontal, arbitrary) line

geom_smooth fits line through data (use at your own "risk")

In [ ]:
# A scatterplot and a threshold
ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + 
    geom_point(shape = 23, fill = "#00CED1", size = 4) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 15, color = "red", size = 2)
In [ ]:
# A scatterplot and a fitted linear model using ordinary least squares
# Geom smooth takes in a method. Use "loess" would create a swiggy line

ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + 
    geom_point(shape = 23, fill = "#00CED1", size = 4) +
    geom_smooth(formula = y ~ x, method = "lm", color = "red", size = 2, se = FALSE)

Oftentimes we want to compare groups using similar aesthetics on a plot.

We do this by setting the aesthetic specifications using value from a third variable.

Stats¶

What are stats?

Stats in ggplot2 are used to transform/summarize the data in a way geoms can unterstand for plotting.

You can imagine stats as the backend, whereas geoms are the frontend of the plot.

In most cases, each stat has a default geom, and each geom has a default stat. We can either use stat (with nested geom) or vice versa to plot.

For example: plot a boxplot with a data column as input. geom_boxplot has the default stat = "boxplot". In this cases, the stat takes raw data, calculates relevant values, passes them to the geom for plotting.

In [ ]:
#Either stat or geom will work

ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) + geom_boxplot(stat = "boxplot") 

ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) + stat_boxplot(geom = "boxplot")

When do stats matter? - Barplot vs Colplot

In many cases, ggplot2 plots the data as is. Thus, many geoms have the default stat = "identity".

In other cases, like the above geom_boxplot, certain transformations need to take place. Other examples include a barplot.

geom_bar has default stat = "count": count observations for a category, then plot the count.

geom_col on the other hand has default stat = identity: it plots the data as is.

In [ ]:
ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = gear)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "count")
In [ ]:
# Manually compute the count table

gearCount <- mtcars %>% group_by(gear) %>% summarize(count = n())
gearCount

# Plot using geom_col
ggplot(data = gearCount, aes(x = as.factor(gear), y = count)) +
    geom_col(stat = "identity")

# Can also use geom_bar (with correct stat)
ggplot(data = gearCount, aes(x = as.factor(gear), y = count)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity")

A boxplot with whiskers

In [ ]:
# (A boxplot on top of an errorbar)

ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg)) + 
    geom_errorbar(stat = "boxplot", width = 0.1) +
    geom_boxplot(stat = "boxplot")

Accessing calculated values from stats

Take histogram. Though we only call one variable in aes, the function actually needed two variables.

stat_bin() calculates additional variables, which can be called using ..<VARIABLE NAME>... Check out https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/ggplot2/versions/1.0.1/topics/stat_bin for the list of variables.

Here, variable y = ..count.. was used.

We can change what is plotted on the y axis to y = ..density..

In [ ]:
ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = ..density..)) + geom_histogram(stat = "bin")

Positions¶

Positions for (grouped) barplots

For this, we work with dataset diamonds.

We want to count the number of diamonds with different colors, while grouped by different types of cut (2 categorical variables).

There are three positions to display the bar plot: stack, dodge and fill

In [ ]:
head(diamonds)
In [ ]:
# Stack: default

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = color, fill = cut)) + geom_bar(position = "stack")
In [ ]:
# Dodge: side-by-side

ggplot(diamonds, aes(color, fill = cut)) + geom_bar(position = "dodge")
In [ ]:
# Fill: Percentage

ggplot(diamonds, aes(color, fill = cut)) + geom_bar(position = "fill")

Labels, Scales & Legends¶

A good enough plot?

Is the following plot good enough to be published?

In [ ]:
ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + 
    geom_point(aes(color = as.factor(cyl), shape = as.factor(gear)), size = 3, alpha = 0.7)

Adding labels

Labeling is a crucial step to make plot readable (not everybody knows what the abbreviated variable names mean)

labs() is used for this purpose.

In [ ]:
ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + 
    geom_point(aes(color = as.factor(cyl), shape = as.factor(gear)), size = 3, alpha = 0.7) +
    labs(title = "Cars specs comparison", 
         subtitle = "Horsepower vs miles/gallon",
         x = "Miles/gallon",
         y = "Horsepower")

Modifying scales

Legend is the area describing (grouped) elements in the graph.

Scales are "dimensions" of the plot. They influences the translation from data to visualization. How many dimensions are there in the plot above?

In [ ]:
# The scales are automatically called with plots, we can make adjustments within the scales

# Change scale name
# Change axis breaks

ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + 
    geom_point(aes(color = as.factor(cyl), shape = as.factor(gear)), size = 3, alpha = 0.7) +

    scale_x_continuous(name = "Miles/gallon", breaks = seq(10, 35, 4)) +
    scale_y_continuous(name = "Horsepower") +
    scale_color_discrete() +
    scale_shape_discrete() +

    labs(title = "Cars specs comparison", 
         subtitle = "Horsepower vs miles/gallon")

Changing legends

Legend is the area describing (grouped) elements in the graph, including the legend title and key values.

Everything looks much clearer now.

In [ ]:
ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + 
    geom_point(aes(color = as.factor(cyl), shape = as.factor(gear)), size = 3, alpha = 0.7) +

    scale_color_discrete(name = "# of cylinders") +
    scale_shape_discrete(name = "# of gears", label = c("Three","Four","Five")) +

    labs(title = "Cars specs comparison", 
         subtitle = "Horsepower vs miles/gallon") +
    xlab("Miles/gallon") +
    ylab("Horsepower")

Hiding legends

In geom layer, add show.legend = F

In [ ]:
ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + 
    geom_point(aes(color = as.factor(cyl), shape = as.factor(gear)), show.legend = F, size = 3, alpha = 0.7) +
    labs(title = "Cars specs comparison", 
         subtitle = "Horsepower vs miles/gallon") +
    xlab("Miles/gallon") +
    ylab("Horsepower")

Facetting¶

Making subplots

Facetting helps you split your data into groups and plot them side-by-side in a similar way for comparison.

facet_wrap turns a long chain of subplots into rows & columns.

facet_grid expands a plot into subplots based on the categories of two variables.

In [ ]:
# Facet wrap
options(repr.plot.width=7, repr.plot.height=5, repr.plot.res = 100) # Set plot size

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = price)) + 
    geom_density(aes(fill = cut, color = cut), alpha = 0.4) + 
    scale_fill_discrete(name = "Types of cut") + 
    scale_color_discrete(name = "Types of cut") +
    geom_vline(xintercept = mean(diamonds$price), alpha = 0.5, linetype = 2) +
    labs(title = "Diamond price distribution across types of cuts", subtitle = "(with overall average price as reference)",
        x = "Price (in USD)",
        y = "Density") +

    facet_wrap(cut ~ ., ncol = 3)
In [ ]:
# We subset data based on two variables with facet_grid

ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + 
    geom_point(aes(color = as.factor(cyl), shape = as.factor(gear)), show.legend = F, size = 3, alpha = 0.7) +
    labs(title = "Cars specs comparison", 
         subtitle = "Horsepower vs miles/gallon") +
    xlab("Miles/gallon") +
    ylab("Horsepower") +
    facet_grid(cyl ~ gear) # here is the subset

Long- & Wide-Format¶

Plotting groups

Long-format: think vertical. A column contains the categories, another contains values.

ggplot2 needs long-format data to plot groups.

In [ ]:
options(repr.plot.width=6, repr.plot.height=4, repr.plot.res = 100)

diamonds %>% select(cut, price) %>% head(10)

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = price)) + 
    geom_density(aes(fill = cut, color = cut), alpha = 0.4) + 
    scale_fill_discrete(name = "Types of cut") + 
    scale_color_discrete(name = "Types of cut") +
    geom_vline(xintercept = mean(diamonds$price), alpha = 0.5, linetype = 2) +
    labs(title = "Diamond price distribution across types of cuts", subtitle = "(with overall average price as reference)",
        x = "Price (in USD)",
        y = "Density")

Convert wide to long data

Some dataset are in wide-format. Wide-format: think horizontal. One row is one observation.

Use pivot_longer from package tidyr for the conversion.

Example with iris dataset: Plot distribution densities of the given features of the flowers

In [ ]:
head(iris)
In [ ]:
irisLong <- iris %>% pivot_longer(cols = -Species, names_to = "Features", values_to = "Measurement")
head(irisLong, 10)
In [ ]:
# Now you can create some plots with the data

irisLong %>% ggplot(aes(x = Measurement, fill = Features)) + geom_density(position = "dodge", alpha = 0.6)
irisLong %>% ggplot(aes(x = Features, y = Measurement, fill = Features)) + geom_errorbar(stat = "boxplot", width = 0.3) + geom_boxplot(show.legend = F)

Coordinates¶

The axes

Coordinates deals with the two axes x and y (here we deal with linear coordinates).

Zoom in/out

In [ ]:
p <- ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) + 
    geom_point(aes(color = as.factor(cyl), shape = as.factor(gear)), size = 3, alpha = 0.7) +
    labs(title = "Cars specs comparison", 
         subtitle = "Horsepower vs miles/gallon",
         x = "Miles/gallon",
         y = "Horsepower") +
    scale_color_discrete(name = "# of cylinders") +
    scale_shape_discrete(name = "# of gears", label = c("Three","Four","Five"))


p

p + coord_cartesian(xlim = c(15, 25))

Plotting a cut of data vs. Looking at a cut of the plotted data

Both coord_cartesian and scale_x_continuous have options to limit the data shown in the plot, but in different ways.

In [ ]:
p2 <- ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = price)) + geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "grey", bins = 20)

p2

p2 + coord_cartesian(xlim = c(5000, 10000)) + labs(title = "Zoom in the coordinate (plot data then look at a cut)")

p2 + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(5000, 10000))  + labs(title = "Zoom in the scale (plot a cut of data)")

Flip the coordinates

In [ ]:
p + coord_flip()

Themes¶

Aesthetic customization

Again, theme() has all the control power of all non-data ink, it's the source of (endless) aesthetic customization in ggplot2.

set_theme sets the overall, pre-defined theme.

For further adjustments, look into the documentation to see what it can influence.

Each component in the plot falls into one of these placeholders:

  • element_text
  • element_line
  • element_rect
  • element_blank

Change plot title text color

In [ ]:
p + theme(plot.title = element_text(color = "blue"))

Rotate the labels on x axis

In [ ]:
options(repr.plot.width=3, repr.plot.height=3, repr.plot.res = 150)

p3 <- irisLong %>% ggplot(aes(x = Features, y = Measurement, fill = Features)) + geom_errorbar(stat = "boxplot", width = 0.3) + geom_boxplot(show.legend = F)

# Rotate label 20 and nudge it down a bit (0.6)
p3 + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 20, vjust = 0.6))

options(repr.plot.width=6, repr.plot.height=4, repr.plot.res = 150)

Make the gridlines disappear

In [ ]:
options(repr.plot.width=6, repr.plot.height=4, repr.plot.res = 100)

p + theme(panel.grid = element_blank())

Wrap legends in boxes

In [ ]:
p + theme(legend.background = element_rect(color = "gold"))

Buffer/Paddling spaces on scale (and how to eliminate them)

In [ ]:
p + scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0.1, 0.1)) +
    scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0 ,0))

Dual Y axis

In [ ]:
meanHp = mtcars %>% group_by(gear) %>% summarize(meanHp = mean(hp))

meanHp

ggplot(mtcars) + 
    
    # Build a normal bar plot counting the number of gears
    geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = as.factor(gear), fill = as.factor(cyl))) + 

    # Plot the lines and points of the second Y axis, "transforming" the values of
    # the second Y axis according to the first one
    geom_line(data = meanHp, mapping = aes(x = as.factor(gear), y = meanHp/10, group = 1), linetype = 2) + 
    geom_point(data = meanHp, mapping = aes(x = as.factor(gear), y = meanHp/10), shape = 21, fill = "blue", color = "black", size = 5) + 
    
    # Set up the two Y axis, transforming back the second one
    scale_y_continuous(name = "Count",
                       sec.axis = sec_axis(trans = ~.*10,
                                           name = "Mean Hp")) +
    
    # Aesthetics setup
    scale_fill_brewer(name = "# of cylinders", palette = "Set1") +
    labs(title = "Distribution of cars based on numbers of gear", 
         subtitle = "with average Horsepower of each group",
         x = "Number of gears") +
    theme(axis.title.y.right = element_text(color = "blue"))
